    <!-- IPI -->
    <section id="ipi" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-10 items-start">
        <div>
          <p class="uppercase tracking-wide text-xs font-semibold mb-2" style="color: #c44a08;">Technology 01</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">IPI: Intermittent Pilot Ignition</h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">IPI fires a spark to light the pilot only when the fireplace is actually called to operate. When the fireplace shuts off, the pilot extinguishes. No standing flame. No gas burned between uses.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">What the older system did</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">A standing pilot system burns a continuous small flame 24 hours a day, 365 days a year. The flame is there to ignite the main burner whenever the thermostat or switch calls for it. The problem is the timing: the fireplace is in active use for a fraction of the hours it burns gas. A family running a gas fireplace through a Minnesota winter might use it 300 hours. The standing pilot burns for roughly 8,760. The gas consumed between uses is pure waste, and the continuous heat cycle stresses the thermocouple and valve components that make up the ignition circuit.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">How IPI works</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">IPI replaces the standing flame with an electronic spark ignition system, the same basic technology used in most gas ranges and outdoor grills. When the fireplace receives an on-signal, the ignition module generates a spark at the pilot. The spark lights the pilot. The pilot lights the main burner. The sequence takes seconds. When the fireplace shuts off, the pilot valve closes and the flame goes out.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The system requires a power source for the ignition electronics. Most Heat & Glo IPI systems include a battery backup so the fireplace remains operational during a power outage. This matters in the cold-weather markets where fireplaces are most frequently used. A power outage in January is exactly when you want the fireplace to work.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Why HHT engineered it this way</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The math is straightforward. Gas consumed only during active use costs substantially less than gas consumed continuously. The component argument is equally clear: a thermocouple and pilot valve cycling on demand last significantly longer than the same components running under continuous heat load. IPI reduces operating cost and extends component life in the same design decision.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">There is also a safety dimension. A fireplace that holds no standing flame between uses eliminates the small but real risk associated with a continuously burning gas flame in a residential space. IPI systems include flame sensing that shuts the pilot if the flame does not light within the expected number of ignition attempts, preventing unburned gas from accumulating.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Where you find IPI in the lineup</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">IPI is standard or available across Heat & Glo's <a href="/fireplaces/gas/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">gas fireplace families</a>, including the Mezzo, Primo II, and True series, and is included in <a href="/fireplaces/inserts/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">gas inserts</a>. Confirm availability on specific models with your authorized dealer.</p>
        </div>
