        <div class="order-1 md:order-2">
          <p class="uppercase tracking-wide text-xs font-semibold mb-2" style="color: #c44a08;">Technology 02</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">Direct-vent: sealed combustion design</h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">A direct-vent fireplace draws all combustion air from outside the home and exhausts all combustion gases back outside through a sealed co-axial pipe system. The firebox is completely sealed from the room it sits in. Indoor air quality is not affected. A chimney is not required.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">The problem with open-combustion and B-vent systems</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Older gas fireplaces and B-vent gas appliances draw combustion air from the room they occupy. This creates two problems. First, the combustion process consumes indoor air that has already been heated or cooled at the homeowner's expense. Second, the exhaust path relies on a chimney that creates a draft pulling warm indoor air up and out, compounding the efficiency loss. In a tightly sealed modern home with mechanical ventilation, this can create negative indoor pressure issues and back-drafting risks.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Open-combustion systems also introduce combustion byproducts into the indoor environment if anything disrupts the draft. High winds, a blocked flue, and changes in indoor-outdoor pressure differential can all affect the draft direction of an open combustion system.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">How the co-axial pipe system works</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Direct-vent systems use a pipe-within-a-pipe arrangement. Fresh outdoor air flows into the firebox through the outer pipe. Combustion exhaust flows out through the inner pipe, in the opposite direction, through the same wall penetration. The two air streams do not mix. The exhaust exits at a low temperature compared to a wood-burning chimney system, which allows the pipe to terminate through a wall rather than requiring a tall vertical flue.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The sealing of the firebox from the room is complete. The glass panel on the front of the firebox is gasketed to maintain the sealed envelope. This is why the glass can get hot: it is the only surface separating the combustion chamber from the room, and the combustion heat transfers through it. It is also why the glass stays clean compared to an open-combustion fireplace: the sealed system controls the combustion environment precisely.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">What this means for installation flexibility</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The absence of a chimney requirement changes where a fireplace can be installed. An interior wall in a room that was never designed to have a fireplace is a viable location. A basement room with no exterior chimney can accommodate a direct-vent gas fireplace. A bedroom, a study, a primary bath, a garage-turned-living-space, all locations where a traditional wood-burning or B-vent fireplace would require significant structural work become straightforward installations.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Vent routing, the path the co-axial pipe takes from the firebox to the exterior, still requires careful planning and confirmation by the installing dealer. Every installation has unique routing constraints based on wall construction, floor framing, and exterior termination options. The authorized dealer will confirm the specific routing before rough-in.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Where you find direct-vent in the lineup</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Direct-vent sealed combustion is the primary system across Heat & Glo's entire <a href="/fireplaces/gas/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">gas fireplace lineup</a>, including the Mezzo, Primo II, and True families, as well as <a href="/fireplaces/see-through/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">see-through configurations</a> and <a href="/fireplaces/inserts/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">gas inserts</a>.</p>
        </div>
