    <!-- Cool-glass -->
    <section id="cool-glass" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-10 items-start">
        <div>
          <p class="uppercase tracking-wide text-xs font-semibold mb-2" style="color: #c44a08;">Technology 03</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">Cool-glass technology</h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Cool-glass is an engineered air-flow system that manages the front-glass surface temperature on a sealed direct-vent firebox. The system circulates a controlled stream of air between the firebox frame and the glass face, reducing the exterior surface temperature while maintaining the full radiant heat output and the wide, unobstructed flame view that contemporary fireplace designs require.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Why the glass temperature problem exists</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">A direct-vent sealed firebox concentrates combustion heat behind a single glass panel. The glass is strong enough to withstand the thermal cycle, but the exterior surface can reach temperatures that pose a burn risk if touched, particularly for children and adults who do not recognize a hot glass surface as a hazard. Consumer product safety standards and manufacturer liability both create strong pressure to manage glass surface temperatures below defined thresholds.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The challenge is that the glass face is also the primary radiant surface. Blocking or reflecting heat away from the glass to reduce surface temperature compromises the radiant heating performance that makes the fireplace useful. The engineering goal is to manage contact-surface temperature without reducing radiant output.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">How the air-flow system manages it</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Cool-glass systems use convective air circulation directed specifically at the space between the outer frame of the firebox and the glass face. Air enters at the base of the firebox surround, flows upward along the glass face, picks up heat from the glass exterior surface, and exits at the top. This continuous air movement carries heat away from the glass surface before it accumulates to high levels.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The air circulation also benefits the room's heating performance. The warmed air that exits at the top of the firebox contributes to room convection, adding to the radiant heat the glass emits. The thermal management and the room heating work together rather than against each other.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">What this means in practice</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Reduced glass surface temperatures lower the risk of contact burns from accidental or curious touch. This is particularly relevant in households with young children and in commercial or hospitality applications where unaccompanied visitors may approach a burning fireplace. Reduced surface temperature does not eliminate burn risk from sustained contact; the glass is still hot during operation. But it meaningfully reduces the severity and speed of a brief accidental contact.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">For specifiers: glass temperature performance data is available for specific models through the ProAdvantage trade program. If your project has specific surface temperature requirements, confirm the data against your applicable standards before finalizing specifications.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Where you find cool-glass in the lineup</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Cool-glass technology is incorporated across the primary Heat & Glo gas fireplace families, including the <a href="/fireplaces/gas/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">Mezzo, Primo II, and True series</a>. Specific model-level data is available through your <a href="/where-to-buy/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">authorized dealer</a>.</p>
        </div>
