        <div class="order-1 md:order-2">
          <p class="uppercase tracking-wide text-xs font-semibold mb-2" style="color: #c44a08;">Technology 04</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">EPA-certified wood combustion</h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Heat & Glo's wood-burning fireplaces are certified to meet the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's emissions standards for residential wood-heating appliances. EPA certification is not a marketing label. It is third-party lab testing against specific particulate output limits, with listed efficiency ratings required on every certified unit.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">What the EPA regulates and why</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The EPA regulates particulate emissions from residential wood-burning heaters under authority established by the Clean Air Act. Wood smoke contains fine particulate matter (PM2.5) that penetrates deep into lung tissue and contributes to both local air quality problems and regional haze. Dense residential areas where many homes burn wood simultaneously can see air quality impacts that rival industrial sources on high-use winter days.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The EPA's Phase II standards tightened the emissions limits that residential wood heaters must meet. Units sold after the effective date of Phase II must be tested by an accredited laboratory and certified to emit no more than a defined quantity of particulate per hour of operation. The test methodology controls fuel type, moisture content, and burn rate to ensure results are comparable across manufacturers.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">What certification actually requires from the engineering</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Meeting EPA Phase II limits requires specific combustion chamber design. The geometry of the combustion chamber, the location and sizing of the air supply openings, and the temperature maintained in the secondary combustion zone all affect particulate output. A poorly designed combustion chamber produces incomplete burns with high particulate emissions. An engineered chamber brings secondary combustion air in at temperatures and velocities that promote complete combustion of volatile gases before they exit as smoke.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Heat & Glo's certified wood-burning models have combustion chambers designed to meet the EPA standard, not to approach it marginally. The engineering choices that produce a low-particulate burn also produce a more efficient burn: more of the fuel's energy is converted to heat rather than lost as unburned compounds in the exhaust stream. The environmental performance and the heating performance point in the same direction.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Efficiency ratings and what they mean</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every EPA-certified wood-burning heater carries a listed efficiency rating. This number represents the percentage of the fuel's heat energy that is transferred to the living space rather than lost up the flue. A unit rated at 75% efficiency delivers three-quarters of the wood's available energy as usable heat. The balance exits as exhaust.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Efficiency ratings are listed in the product's documentation and on the EPA's certified wood heater database. Your authorized dealer can provide the specific efficiency data for any Heat & Glo wood-burning unit.</p>

          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-2">Where you find EPA-certified combustion in the lineup</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">EPA Phase II certification applies to Heat & Glo's <a href="/fireplaces/wood/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">wood-burning fireplace lineup</a>. Specific efficiency and emissions data for each model is available through your <a href="/where-to-buy/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">authorized dealer</a> or the <a href="/about-us/epa-certification/" class="underline" style="color: #c44a08;">EPA certification information page</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

