    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">Technical questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-6 max-w-3xl">
        <details class="border rounded-lg">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold cursor-pointer hover:bg-neutral-50">Can I switch between IPI and standing pilot mode?</summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Many Heat & Glo gas fireplaces with IPI offer a standing pilot mode as an option, selectable at the control module. This can be useful in extremely cold climates where the pilot acts as a minor heat source that helps prevent condensation in the firebox. Confirm the available modes for your specific model with your authorized dealer before purchase if this matters for your installation.</div>
        </details>
        <details class="border rounded-lg">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold cursor-pointer hover:bg-neutral-50">What is the vent termination requirement for direct-vent fireplaces?</summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Vent termination requirements vary by model, local building code, and the specific vent path. General requirements include minimum clearances from windows, doors, and air intake openings, and specific clearances from grade. Your local building department and your authorized dealer can confirm the termination requirements for your installation before rough-in. Do not assume vent termination from a neighboring installation or a previous project without checking the specific model's requirements against your local code.</div>
        </details>
        <details class="border rounded-lg">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold cursor-pointer hover:bg-neutral-50">Does EPA certification affect what wood I can burn?</summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Yes. EPA certification testing uses seasoned cordwood of defined moisture content. Burning wet or unseasoned wood in an EPA-certified fireplace produces substantially more particulate than the certified level, defeats the combustion engineering designed into the unit, and accelerates creosote buildup in the flue. For an EPA-certified fireplace to perform as rated, use properly seasoned wood with moisture content below 20%, confirmed with a wood moisture meter.</div>
        </details>
        <details class="border rounded-lg">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold cursor-pointer hover:bg-neutral-50">Can a direct-vent gas fireplace be converted to use a different fuel?</summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Heat & Glo gas fireplaces are available in either natural gas or liquid propane configurations. Many models include a conversion kit that allows field conversion between fuel types. The conversion requires a qualified gas technician and must be performed according to the installation manual. A direct-vent gas fireplace cannot be converted to a wood-burning unit.</div>
        </details>
        <details class="border rounded-lg">
          <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold cursor-pointer hover:bg-neutral-50">What does a spec professional need to know about direct-vent gas when framing begins?</summary>
          <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">The framing crew needs the firebox dimensions, the vent pipe diameter and routing path, the wall penetration location, and the clearance-to-combustibles requirements from the specific model's installation manual. These are available through your authorized dealer or through the ProAdvantage trade portal. Do not frame the opening based on a similar previous project without confirming against the specific unit being installed. Firebox dimensions and vent requirements vary between models and within the same family across sizes.</div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

